{"sessionId": "71f2c0", "runId": "pre-fix", "hypothesisId": "H1-H5", "location": "controller/text_generation.py:62", "message": "generate_text succeeded with raw patterns payload", "data": {"raw_text": "```json\n{\n  \"hero_summary\": \"You seem to experience patterns of uncertainty and feeling overwhelmed in various situations, while also frequently finding relief, happiness, and calm through successful completions and undistracted moments.\",\n  \"short_summary\": \"Your emotional experiences often involve feelings of doubt and unease, particularly when reflecting on your progress compared to others or in response to family inquiries about your future, and also anxiety linked to academic or task-related uncertainties. On the more positive side, you frequently feel relieved or happy after successfully completing tasks or engaging in physical activities, and you tend to find calm in focused, undistracted moments.\",\n  \"quick_insights\": [\n    \"Uncertainty about performance may lead to repeated checking or rumination.\",\n    \"Social comparisons can often spark feelings of self-doubt.\",\n    \"Multiple incoming demands tend to result in feeling overwhelmed.\",\n    \"Interactions with family members sometimes bring frustration or unease.\",\n    \"Successfully completing tasks frequently brings a sense of relief or happiness.\",\n    \"Focused, calm moments seem to contribute to a sense of well-being.\"\n  ],\n  \"detailed_summary\": \"A significant pattern for you involves experiencing feelings of doubt and unease, often triggered by social comparisons or inquiries from family members. For example, you tend to feel doubtful when comparing your class progress or presentation slides to others (Log 35, Log 53), leading to a sense of feeling behind or less polished. Similarly, conversations with your dad about future plans or progress (Log 36, Log 64) or a comment from your sister (Log 75) can leave you feeling uneasy, often prompting lingering thoughts and uncertainty about your responses. It appears that these instances often lead to internal rumination, even if you do not have clear evidence for the negative feelings or do not express them directly. \\n\\nAnother frequent pattern involves feelings of anxiety, doubt, or tension, often linked to academic and task-related uncertainties, which can manifest as a tendency to re-check things. You might experience this when submitting an assignment (Log 7), preparing for an exam or interview (Log 26, Log 33), or even when boarding travel (Log 50, Log 81), where you tend to repeatedly verify information or details, often without a clear reason for concern. This often involves rumination about potential omissions or errors after a task is completed (Log 60, Log 74).\\n\\nIn contrast, you frequently experience feelings of relief or happiness, particularly after successful task completion or engaging in physical activity. This might occur after sending a delayed email (Log 12), finishing a presentation smoothly (Log 27, Log 56), or when a task goes as planned (Log 80). You also tend to feel happy or stronger after positive physical experiences like a good run or gym session (Log 40, Log 59). These experiences often leave you feeling more controlled, relaxed, or with an improved mood.\\n\\nYou also seem to encounter frustration or irritation in interactions with family members, especially your sister and mom. This can happen when your sister moves your belongings (Log 32), interrupts your work (Log 8, Log 61), or doesn't follow through on promises (Log 19), or when your mom appears distracted during conversations (Log 42, Log 82). In these situations, you often find yourself feeling annoyed or unheard, but you tend not to address the issue directly, sometimes because it 'didn't feel worth it' or 'felt normal.'\\n\\nAdditionally, you often feel overwhelmed when confronted with multiple simultaneous demands or incoming messages. This pattern emerges when you receive a flurry of notifications from school, work, and family (Log 20, Log 58, Log 79) or when you have several overlapping responsibilities (Log 30, Log 48). In such moments, you may find it difficult to prioritize or focus, leading to a sense of being pulled in 'too many directions at once.'\\n\\nYou also show a pattern of irritation in response to external distractions or perceived inefficiencies in your environment. This might include waiting for gym equipment being used inefficiently by others (Log 28, Log 45), being in a crowded line (Log 66), or encountering repetitive questions or noise during important tasks like presentations or exams (Log 77, Log 57). These situations can make it harder for you to focus, and the annoyance tends to linger, often without being expressed.\\n\\nConversely, you often experience feelings of calm or satisfaction when engaging in undistracted activities or when you find clarity. This may include walking without headphones and paying attention to your surroundings (Log 9), sitting in a caf' without pressure to be productive (Log 34), or organizing notes with clear steps (Log 72). These moments often bring a sense of quietness, focus, or lack of urgency.\\n\\nSeparately, you tend to feel curious when you encounter new ideas, specializations, or career paths. This can be sparked by overhearing conversations (Log 24, Log 44) or by discovering different project types online (Log 62, Log 83), often leading you to consider exploring these areas further.\\n\\nYou also seem to experience conflicted feelings when faced with choices, especially between social desires and responsibilities or when unsure about your own motivations. This might arise when weighing a social invitation against your workload (Log 49) or when you are debating whether to text someone, uncertain of the underlying reason (Log 70).\\n\\nFinally, you may experience unease from brief or seemingly distant interactions with your mom. This pattern is noted when she sounds rushed on the phone (Log 29) or sends a short text about being busy (Log 55). These instances can leave you feeling like something is 'slightly off' or suggest a sense of distance, and these feelings tend to linger.\"\n}\n```"}, "timestamp": 1775674983405}
